job_description_director.content:
Place in the organization
As director ultimately responsible for the entire company. Reports to the shareholders.

Is ultimately responsible and ensures the implementation of:
- the business policy;
- the OHS policy;
- the personnel policy.

Tasks and responsibilities
- safeguarding the continuity of the enterprise;
- maintaining contacts with clients, subcontractors and other stakeholders;
- the assessment of the management system;
- periodically (at least 4 times a year) carrying out a workplace inspection;
- organizing consultations (including toolbox meetings);
- guidance of employees;
- daily implementation of personnel, OHS and training policy;
- handling complaints, shortcomings, accidents and incidents and reporting.

Replacement
The director is replaced by the administration for administrative and financial matters and by the executor for project matters.

job_description_executor.content:
Place in the organization
As an operational manager, accountable to the director.

Tasks and responsibilities
- daily execution of the project and the associated safeguarding of OHS;
- ensuring an efficient work sequence and layout;
- material and equipment management at the work location;
- enforcement and coordination of rules regarding safety, health, and environment at the workplace (OHS-project coordinator);
- maintaining contacts on behalf of the company with: supervisors from/on behalf of clients, residents, in some cases with clients, if necessary together with the executor, other stakeholders;
- training new employees;
- stopping work in case of imminent danger to safety, health, or the environment;
- giving instructions and assignments to employees.

Replacement
The executor is replaced by the director, a colleague executor, or an experienced foreman.

Job requirements
- MBO-level in a technical field;
- valid certificate Safety for Operational Managers VCA (VOL-VCA);
- valid Driving License BE

rie.content:
The OHS officer has, in accordance with legal requirements, in cooperation with the external safety expert, prepared an RIE. This RIE explicitly addresses the inventory of operational activities, associated hazards, and risk assessment.

Effective measures for risks are established in the action plan, with source control preferred. Action items, responsible parties for execution, and deadlines are recorded.

The RIE and action plan are periodically (at least every three years) evaluated (and adjusted if necessary) based on:
- reports of accidents and incidents;
- results of workplace inspections;
- results of TRA's;
- changes in legislation;
- changes in the work environment and work activities;
- advancing technology.

tra.content:
Risks may arise from work activities that are not included in the RIE (for example, due to a specific work environment or when deviating from a common work method). A TRA is prepared for each job.

If this is not the case, the line manager involved in the execution of the work, possibly supported by a safety expert, prepares a TRA. The involved line manager has the authority to stop work if the risks are too great.

This TRA addresses:
- The tasks to be performed;
- The associated risks;
- The measures to be taken, with source control preferred;
- Communication of the TRA with all executors and involved parties by the TRA preparer.

After every accident with absence, the TRA is evaluated and adjusted if necessary.
